## 1. Starting the agent

```bash
cd <this-directory>
./bootstrap.sh           # one-shot setup
```

Then message the agent on {{provider_label}}. The first message you send triggers the agent's onboarding interview — it will ask about you (operator name, role, organization, hierarchy, tasks, tone, sensitive data). The agent fills in the `{{slots}}` it sees in `CLAUDE.md` and persona docs as it learns.

You don't need to answer everything in one session. The agent iterates.

---

## 2. `/loop` mechanics (heartbeat cadence)

The agent runs a recurring heartbeat via Claude Code's `/loop` skill. Standard pattern:

```
/loop 30m run the heartbeat per personas/{{persona_name}}/CLAUDE.md (drain processing/ then inbox/, memory log, active-build state). If nothing to do, reply HEARTBEAT_OK and stop.
```

Cron-style shorthand:

| You want | Cron |
|---|---|
| every 5 min | `*/5 * * * *` |
| every 20 min | `*/20 * * * *` (or pick off-peak: `7,27,47 * * * *`) |
| every 30 min | `*/30 * * * *` (or `7,37 * * * *` to avoid global pile-up) |
| hourly | `0 * * * *` (or `7 * * * *`) |
| weekdays 9am | `0 9 * * 1-5` |

### ⚠️ The 7-day auto-expiry gotcha

`CronCreate` (the tool behind `/loop`) **auto-deletes recurring tasks after 7 days.** They fire one final time, then disappear. This means:

- After a week, the heartbeat stops firing silently.
- After a `/clear`, **all crons die** — they live only in the session.
- Re-arm the heartbeat every time you `/clear` or restart the session.

The agent knows this and will re-arm itself at session start. If you notice the heartbeat hasn't fired in 30+ min after a restart, message the agent: "are you /loop-ed?"

### Re-arming after `/clear`

```
heartbeat — drain personas/{{persona_name}}/inbox/ ... [full heartbeat instruction]
```

Then the agent re-runs `/loop` with the same cadence.

