## 3. Backup risks + mitigations

⚠️ V1 does NOT configure backups. This is by design — operator-shaped backups (what's worth saving on YOUR machine) are case-by-case.

But the risks are real and worth understanding:

### Why backups matter

The agent runtime holds:
- OAuth tokens (Gmail, Calendar, Slack/Telegram)
- API keys (Anthropic, any vendor seats)
- Accumulated state in `shared/memory/` (months of context — your operator profile, your hierarchy, your patterns)
- Client-specific docs you've shared with the agent

Losing this = full re-pairing cycle with every service AND losing the personalization history.

### Risks

- **Hardware failure** — disk dies; Mac Mini fails.
- **Agent error** — accidental `rm -rf` of a directory.
- **Ransomware / malware.**
- **Drive theft.**
- **Account compromise** — someone gets your laptop login.

### Mitigation options (operator picks)

| Tier | Tool | Coverage | Trade-off |
|---|---|---|---|
| Local snapshot | Time Machine | Files, hourly | Native macOS, easy to set up; tied to one external drive |
| Local snapshot (better) | restic | Files, dedupe, hourly | Cross-platform, snapshots compress/dedupe well |
| Cloud offsite | restic → R2 / B2 / S3 | Survives local disaster | Costs $1–5/mo; needs encryption passphrase backed up SEPARATELY |
| Git-vault | git commit + push to private remote | Granular diff history | Doesn't capture binary/large files cleanly |
| Keychain | `security export` to encrypted file | OAuth + API keys specifically | Easy to forget; manual cadence |

**Recommendation:** at minimum, set up Time Machine. If you trust cloud, layer in `restic → R2` daily. The agent can walk you through any of these via {{provider_label}}.

