## 5. Manual commands (when bootstrap / start.sh / launchd isn't enough)

Most operations go through `./bootstrap.sh` (one-time setup) and `./restart.sh` (after config changes), with launchd keeping the agent alive in the background. These are the underlying commands if you want to run things by hand or debug.

### Launch Claude Code manually (no tmux, no launchd)

```bash
cd <vault-dir>
claude --plugin-dir .claude/plugins/{{provider}}
```

If running headless (no GUI prompt for permission approvals — e.g. a VM, a remote SSH session, a container), add the skip-permissions flag:

```bash
claude --plugin-dir .claude/plugins/{{provider}} --dangerously-skip-permissions
```

### Launch via tmux (matches what `start.sh` does)

```bash
tmux new-session -A -s {{persona_name}} "cd <vault-dir> && claude --plugin-dir .claude/plugins/{{provider}}"
```

Attach to a running session:

```bash
tmux attach -t {{persona_name}}
```

Detach without killing: `Ctrl-b` then `d`.

### Restart

```bash
./restart.sh
```

Or manually: kill the tmux session, then `launchctl kickstart -k gui/$(id -u)/com.{{label}}.{{persona_name}}`.

### Secrets management

```bash
# Set a secret in Keychain (used by the plugin / agent for OAuth tokens, API keys, etc.):
./bootstrap-secret {{label}}_<key-name> <value>

# Example: rotate the messaging-plugin bot token:
./bootstrap-secret {{label}}_{{provider}}_bot_token <new-token>
./restart.sh
```

### Status checks

```bash
# Is the launchd plist loaded?
launchctl list | grep com.{{label}}

# Is the tmux session running?
tmux has-session -t {{persona_name}} && echo "running" || echo "down"

# Tail the persona's recent stdout/stderr (launchd-redirected logs):
tail -f /tmp/{{label}}-{{persona_name}}.{out,err}

# Claude Code version:
claude --version
```

### Reset / clear the session

If the operator says "reset", "clear", or "start fresh":

```bash
bash <vault-dir>/clear-self.sh operator-requested
```

This sends `/clear` to the running session + injects a re-orient prompt. The session loses live context but vault state (memory, drafts, decisions, etc.) persists.

